WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.160
Welcome, everybody, to our final presentation in this programming track.

00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:12.040
I want to introduce you to Jim Hester.

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:17.120
Jim is a software engineer on the Tidyverse team, and he is going to talk about his work

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:18.600
on GitHub Actions.

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:22.920
All right, thanks, everyone, for coming.

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:27.639
As Andre said, I'm Jim Hester, I'm a software engineer at RStudio, and I'm going to talk

00:00:27.639 --> 00:00:30.080
about GitHub Actions for R.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:36.480
So GitHub Actions is a new service recently released by GitHub, and it allows you to automate

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:43.320
common workflows in software packages and in repositories that you have on GitHub.

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:47.840
And one of the most common things that people want to do with these types of services is

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:51.320
what's called continuous integration, or CI.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:57.520
And continuous integration is, if you're not familiar with it, it's a way to run your

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:03.040
all the tests and checks on your project every time you make a change to the project.

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:08.400
So if you commit a change to the repo, or if someone submits a pull request to your

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:17.239
repo, continuous integration would run all of the package checks on that new code to

00:01:17.239 --> 00:01:20.919
verify that it doesn't break your existing functionality.

00:01:20.919 --> 00:01:25.480
And this is a really great way to make sure that you don't accidentally break something,

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:30.680
and also to give you confidence that the user, the person who submitted the pull request

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:34.080
to you, isn't going to break something in your project.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:38.760
And this is also a good way to ensure your project is reproducible, because the code

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:45.519
is running on someone else's machine, which is really one of the first steps in reproducibility.

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:50.559
So Martin Fowler has this famous quote that, if it hurts, you should do it more often.

00:01:50.559 --> 00:01:55.800
And that's really the crux of continuous integration.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.720
Rather than running your tests maybe only before you do a CRAN release or a big release

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:03.040
of your package, you run the tests every time you make a change.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:09.240
And that really makes sure that if you introduce a bug, it's only going to be a bug in a very

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:12.880
small subset of your package, because it's only the things that have changed since the

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:18.559
last time you ran a successful test.

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:20.759
So what does this actually look like on GitHub?

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:27.240
So this is all of the commits in one of my repositories, the Vroom repository.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:32.679
And next to each commit, you can see there's, it's kind of small, but there's a green check

00:02:32.679 --> 00:02:37.279
mark next to some, or a red X next to some others.

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:43.839
And this is showing the check status of the checks that I ran on GitHub Actions for each

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:44.839
of those commits.

00:02:45.279 --> 00:02:50.279
And if you click on one of these, the red check marks, it'll give you a more detailed

00:02:50.279 --> 00:02:52.759
view of all of the checks that were run.

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:55.800
So here I'm running checks on multiple different operating systems.

00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:01.720
And you can see the Windows and macOS checks worked fine, but all of the checks on Linux

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:02.839
seems to have broke.

00:03:02.839 --> 00:03:07.520
So clearly, that gives you some idea of where the problem might lie already.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:14.520
And if you need more detail, there's a live log for the checks, and you can find exactly

00:03:15.199 --> 00:03:20.600
what line might have caused the error.

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:25.119
So this GitHub Actions is not the only service that provides these sort of features.

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:30.919
So why might GitHub Actions be a good thing for you to try on your repository?

00:03:30.919 --> 00:03:37.919
The first thing is that it's one of the few services that has support for multiple, all

00:03:38.919 --> 00:03:44.720
three major operating systems, Linux, Windows, and macOS.

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:47.399
And it also has first class support for Docker containers.

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:52.279
So if your package or your project, if you're used to working in Docker containers, and

00:03:52.279 --> 00:03:55.559
you have all of your dependencies already bundled into a Docker container, you can use

00:03:55.559 --> 00:03:59.279
those on GitHub Actions very easily.

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:04.399
It also has very generous resource allocations for your jobs.

00:04:04.399 --> 00:04:08.559
So you can run 20 concurrent jobs for a given repository.

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:12.800
And those jobs can take up to six hours.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:18.279
And because GitHub Actions is built into GitHub, it doesn't require separate authentication

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:22.040
and setup steps apart from your regular GitHub authentication.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:27.760
So as soon as you commit the configuration file that describes your workflow to your

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:30.839
repository, it's going to start running on GitHub Actions.

00:04:30.839 --> 00:04:35.679
You don't have to do any additional manual setup.

00:04:35.679 --> 00:04:37.880
And you might ask, is this service free?

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:43.359
And it is for open source, academic, and educational repositories.

00:04:43.359 --> 00:04:47.519
If you don't fall into one of those buckets, you can still use GitHub Actions, but you

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:52.700
have to pay a fairly reasonable fee.

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:57.640
So I mentioned there were some other services that do similar things to what GitHub Actions

00:04:57.640 --> 00:04:59.480
provides.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:05.480
Some of the most popular that are used in the R community are Travis CI, CircleCI, and

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:06.600
AppVeyor.

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:10.239
You can see compared to these, GitHub Actions is one of the few that has support for all

00:05:10.239 --> 00:05:14.559
of these three operating systems and really good support for Docker containers.

00:05:14.559 --> 00:05:19.119
And then it also gives you many more concurrent builds than the other services provide for

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:21.079
open source projects.

00:05:21.079 --> 00:05:25.799
And the maximum job length is the longest of any of the other options.

00:05:25.799 --> 00:05:31.160
And again, in terms of setup, because this is integrated into GitHub, it's basically

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:37.200
painless to set up, whereas some of the other services range from moderately annoying to

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:40.640
extremely annoying.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:46.079
So you might have noticed that in my talk abstract, it was about Azure Pipelines and

00:05:46.079 --> 00:05:47.079
GitHub Actions.

00:05:47.079 --> 00:05:49.679
So why am I not talking about Azure at all?

00:05:49.679 --> 00:05:56.160
So the first thing is that it is true that Azure Pipelines has been around as a publicly

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:58.739
available service for a lot longer than GitHub Actions.

00:05:58.739 --> 00:06:01.760
So as a result, it's much more mature.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:05.000
There's definitely more features available in Azure.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.760
However, because it's not integrated into GitHub, it's actually much more challenging

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:14.480
to set up and get working on your project.

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:16.920
And they actually share the same infrastructure.

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:20.760
So GitHub Actions is running on the Azure cloud.

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:26.480
And actually, a lot of the code, the backend code, is identical between the two services.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:29.559
So a lot of the features are basically the same between the two.

00:06:29.559 --> 00:06:35.959
And because GitHub Actions is so much easier to get set up, and I think the features are

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:42.200
just going to continue to improve over time, I just would recommend using GitHub Actions.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.519
So how do you actually do this on your repository?

00:06:45.519 --> 00:06:49.519
So in the develop version of the use this package, we have a function called use GitHub

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:50.679
Actions.

00:06:50.679 --> 00:06:53.920
And this will create a workflow configuration file.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:59.559
These are a YAML file, if you're familiar with that format.

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:04.079
And this describes to GitHub Actions the workflow that you want it to perform.

00:07:04.079 --> 00:07:08.839
So at the beginning, we have to tell GitHub Actions what GitHub event we want to run the

00:07:08.839 --> 00:07:11.320
action on, the workflow on.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:15.420
And so in this case, we want to run it any time there's a push to the repository or there's

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:17.980
a pull request.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:23.140
And the next thing we are specifying is what operating system the workflow should run on.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:25.980
In this case, we're running on macOS.

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:28.160
And then we need to check out the code.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:31.859
So this checks out your Git code on the worker.

00:07:31.859 --> 00:07:40.299
And then we set up R using this custom action that I wrote to install R on the worker.

00:07:40.299 --> 00:07:42.179
And then we need to...

00:07:42.179 --> 00:07:45.220
So this is checking an R package.

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:50.820
And those R packages usually have additional packages they depend on.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:56.559
So this set of code is installing the remotes package to install all of the package dependencies

00:07:56.559 --> 00:07:59.619
for the R package we're trying to check.

00:07:59.619 --> 00:08:04.220
And then finally, we can actually run the check on R package with the R command check

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:07.000
package.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.279
So that's the simplest workflow for doing a package check.

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:17.000
In the tidyverse, we try to have a little bit more robust checks.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:26.440
We want to check on more than one operating system and more than one version of R. So

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:27.720
we have this more...

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:28.980
This lengthier...

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.839
So this is the entire file, which obviously you can't read.

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:35.239
But I'm gonna go through some of the features in this.

00:08:35.239 --> 00:08:38.640
And this uses a different function, use GitHub actions tidy.

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:43.320
So the first thing that this does is uses a matrix build, which means that instead of

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:50.119
only building one operating system and one version of R, we're building multiple different

00:08:50.119 --> 00:08:51.119
operating systems.

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:55.479
So we're building on Windows, Mac OS, and Ubuntu Linux.

00:08:55.479 --> 00:09:03.400
And then we're also building on multiple versions of R. So it's building on R Devel, R 3.6,

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:06.239
and all the way back to R 3.2.

00:09:06.239 --> 00:09:11.640
And we do this in the tidyverse packages to ensure that all of our packages work on even

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:14.280
pretty old versions of R.

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:17.599
The last thing this has is RStudio package manager.

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:23.099
It takes advantage of RStudio package manager, which now provides Linux binaries.

00:09:23.099 --> 00:09:28.880
So that really speeds up the installation of installing your package dependencies on

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.719
Linux.

00:09:32.719 --> 00:09:38.599
Another thing that helps with installing package dependencies quickly is package caching, which

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:40.919
GitHub actions also provides.

00:09:40.919 --> 00:09:48.280
And this code that I'm showing here is how you set that up for an R package.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:53.919
Another thing that this workflow does is it automatically will, using the R hub sysrex

00:09:53.919 --> 00:10:01.159
database, it automatically queries any Linux system dependencies that your packages or

00:10:01.159 --> 00:10:04.739
dependencies needs and will automatically install them.

00:10:04.739 --> 00:10:10.799
So rather than having to know about these Linux system dependencies yourself, this will

00:10:10.799 --> 00:10:13.840
query them and install them for you automatically.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:21.000
And then, finally, it's often ‑‑ I guess not quite finally, but when a failure happens,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:28.119
it's often useful to download all of the logs for that check run to your local machine so

00:10:28.119 --> 00:10:31.140
you can inspect them more closely.

00:10:31.140 --> 00:10:38.820
So this chunk of code will, if a failure happens, it will upload all of the check logs as an

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:42.299
artifact of the build so you can download them if you need to.

00:10:42.299 --> 00:10:50.140
And then, finally, we run the ‑‑ we use the cover package to run test coverage on

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:55.539
the R package and use the CodeCov.io service to upload the results and store the results

00:10:55.539 --> 00:10:59.460
of our check coverage.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:02.099
So that was the more complicated workflow.

00:11:02.099 --> 00:11:06.460
We also ‑‑ so I should mention all of these workflows that I'm going through are

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:10.940
available on this GitHub site, github.com slash rlib slash actions.

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:15.059
So it has examples of everything I'm going to be talking about today and all of the custom

00:11:15.059 --> 00:11:18.760
actions that we've built for R packages.

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:22.559
So there's additional workflows that we have available.

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:27.619
So these are three similar workflows for building other things related to R packages.

00:11:27.619 --> 00:11:34.340
So the first one is a workflow that builds the package down site for your R package.

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:39.299
Second one is if you have a blog down site, this will use GitHub actions to build your

00:11:39.299 --> 00:11:42.260
blog down site and deploy it to Netlify.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:48.380
And the third one is if you have a book down book, you can use GitHub actions to build

00:11:48.380 --> 00:11:51.820
your book and then deploy it to Netlify as well.

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:54.979
So these are all fairly similar, so I'm only going to go through one of them, the blog

00:11:54.979 --> 00:11:56.820
down one.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:02.820
And you can add these to your project using the use this, use GitHub action and then the

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:03.820
file name.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:07.299
In this case, it's blog down.yaml.

00:12:07.299 --> 00:12:10.380
So that's the full file.

00:12:10.380 --> 00:12:14.460
So what this does is the first thing is it installs R and Pandoc.

00:12:14.460 --> 00:12:17.619
This is very similar to the workflow we already saw.

00:12:17.619 --> 00:12:22.260
The next thing is for this blog down site, I'm actually going to use the renv package

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:28.500
to track the package dependencies I used in my site and then install exactly the same

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:35.219
versions that I used locally on the GitHub actions worker.

00:12:35.219 --> 00:12:36.260
So that's what this is doing.

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:42.460
And then it's also installing the Hugo web framework that you need for blog down.

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:48.460
And then finally, I can build the site using blog down build site and then deploy the site

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:55.700
to Netlify by installing the Netlify command line tool and then using that to deploy the

00:12:55.700 --> 00:12:57.340
site.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:02.820
So the other thing to point out in this slide is that I'm using a secret.

00:13:02.820 --> 00:13:11.760
So GitHub actions lets you add secrets to your repository in the repository settings.

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:18.320
And then you can use these secrets within your action workflows for doing things like

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:24.099
I'm doing here if I have an authentication token I need.

00:13:24.099 --> 00:13:29.460
So all of the actions I've shown so far have basically used the same event.

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:32.960
So they're running on either a push or a pull request event.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:40.739
But you can actually trigger a GitHub action on any event in a GitHub repository.

00:13:40.739 --> 00:13:46.820
So some examples we have of triggering things on other events are an action that will re-render

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:53.940
a readme.rmd file any time you modify the contents of that file.

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:58.219
So that won't run normally if you're editing something else in your repository.

00:13:58.219 --> 00:14:03.979
But if a given commit or pull request edits something in that readme, then this action

00:14:03.979 --> 00:14:05.460
will run and re-render.

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:09.179
And then actually it will also push the results back to the repository.

00:14:09.179 --> 00:14:14.020
So you don't ever have to do that rendering locally.

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:17.340
The second thing is for...

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:22.419
It's a thing to help package maintainers when they're dealing with pull requests.

00:14:22.419 --> 00:14:30.580
So we have a custom GitHub action that looks for special comments that the package maintainer

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:36.859
posts on a pull request slash document and slash style.

00:14:36.859 --> 00:14:40.659
And GitHub actions uses this event.

00:14:40.659 --> 00:14:47.380
And when those comments appear, it will automatically run devtools document or use the styler package

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:55.500
and restyle the pull request and then push the result of those action, of that code,

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:57.020
back to the pull request.

00:14:57.020 --> 00:15:03.340
So rather than the maintainer having to download the code locally, run, like, devtools document,

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:10.260
submit the result and push it back, they can just comment slash document.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:11.799
GitHub actions will do all of this.

00:15:11.799 --> 00:15:15.700
And then you can go on with your code review.

00:15:15.700 --> 00:15:24.340
Another example is in my personal website on jimhester.com, I have this GitHub-inspired

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:27.500
calendar that is showing, like, all of my activity throughout the year.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.940
And I have to update this every day.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.460
So I build my site with GitHub actions.

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:37.739
And I have a you can schedule an action to run at a certain time.

00:15:37.739 --> 00:15:42.580
So I have this action running every day at 11 o'clock.

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:46.900
And so that way, I don't have to, like, update this manually every day.

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:50.140
So I mentioned GitHub actions has support for Docker containers.

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:51.460
So how would that look?

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:55.619
So this is a simple example of using a Docker container in a GitHub action.

00:15:55.619 --> 00:15:58.299
So you have to specify which container you want to use.

00:15:58.299 --> 00:16:01.580
And this is pulling in this case, I'm using the rocker-verse container.

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:06.179
And this is pulling from the Docker hub.

00:16:06.179 --> 00:16:09.739
So this container is available on Docker hub.

00:16:09.739 --> 00:16:13.859
And it will run all the rest of the code in that container.

00:16:13.859 --> 00:16:17.260
So here I'm fitting a model in one R script.

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:23.219
And then I'm running I'm rendering an RMD file and creating an HTML output and then

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:27.299
uploading that HTML output as an artifact of the build.

00:16:29.859 --> 00:16:37.260
So this presentation was about GitHub Actions for R. This work was done by me.

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:39.900
And also, we had an RStudio intern, Max Held,

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:43.580
who did a lot of the early pioneering work of this over the summer.

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:46.500
So this wouldn't be possible without him.

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:48.900
All of the workflows that I talked about are available on

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:52.340
github.com slash rlib slash actions.

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:54.219
And that also has all of our custom actions.

00:16:54.219 --> 00:16:57.419
So if you're looking for information about using GitHub Actions for R,

00:16:57.419 --> 00:16:59.380
that's the best place to go.

00:16:59.380 --> 00:17:01.500
And if you want to try these out on your repository,

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:04.380
you can go to use this, use GitHub Actions.

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:07.540
And the slides are available on speaker deck at that URL.

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:08.619
So thank you.

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:21.339
That was great.

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:22.939
Thank you very much, Jim.

00:17:22.939 --> 00:17:27.739
The first question is, if you use Azure DevOps for source control,

00:17:27.739 --> 00:17:32.540
do you think the increased difficulty over GitHub Actions is largely eliminated?

00:17:34.819 --> 00:17:37.739
I know basically nothing about Azure DevOps.

00:17:37.739 --> 00:17:38.579
But yeah, I think so.

00:17:38.579 --> 00:17:42.219
I think if you're already like in sort of the Azure ecosystem,

00:17:42.219 --> 00:17:46.380
I think maybe Azure pipelines might work.

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:49.300
But I don't know for sure.

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:50.619
Thank you.

00:17:50.619 --> 00:17:54.979
We have a rather starry-eyed question here, important one.

00:17:54.979 --> 00:17:57.939
How did you make these slides?

