00:18:24.619 --> 00:18:28.380
when testing and checking internal R packages?

00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:31.180
So there are no plans on our team.

00:18:31.939 --> 00:18:35.900
In terms of the Tidyverse team, we're very much, I think,

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:41.459
going to just steer towards GitHub Actions for all of our repositories.

00:18:41.459 --> 00:18:45.859
I think that's probably, for our open source work, I think, and

00:18:45.859 --> 00:18:47.339
we do all of our work on GitHub.

00:18:47.339 --> 00:18:48.780
So I think it makes a lot of sense for

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:51.780
us to invest resources there rather than in Azure.

00:18:53.099 --> 00:18:53.660
Thank you.

00:18:54.859 --> 00:18:58.900
Can you say something about your experience of moving from Travis CI to

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:01.219
GitHub Actions for the Tidyverse project?

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:03.099
Yes, yeah.

00:19:03.099 --> 00:19:08.900
So I think, so we've made Travis,

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:11.780
the configuration you need for Travis, very simple.

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:15.180
Like you can basically just have language R and a couple more lines.

00:19:16.180 --> 00:19:21.020
The workflow files you use in GitHub Actions are a little bit longer.

00:19:21.020 --> 00:19:24.859
But I think some people, when they're using Travis,

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:31.939
don't understand all the steps that are going on when you set language R.

00:19:31.939 --> 00:19:37.459
So part of my motivation in GitHub Actions was to make that a little bit

00:19:37.459 --> 00:19:39.260
more transparent, so it would be easier for

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:41.859
people to understand exactly what was happening.

00:19:41.859 --> 00:19:47.180
And that they could modify it if they need to, yeah.

00:19:47.180 --> 00:19:49.339
Thank you, and I think there's time for one more, perhaps.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:54.219
This person is asking, you mentioned CronTab.

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:57.579
You can schedule kicking off an action.

00:19:57.579 --> 00:20:01.939
Can GitHub Actions be used to provide a package that has data that refreshes

00:20:01.939 --> 00:20:04.060
hourly or at some frequency?

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:05.260
Or are there pros and cons?

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:07.859
Are there reasons why you would not do that?

00:20:07.859 --> 00:20:08.979
You can definitely do that.

00:20:08.979 --> 00:20:16.020
So you can, yeah, you could schedule a GitHub Action to run hourly and

00:20:16.020 --> 00:20:20.099
then deploy, like create data and then deploy it wherever.

00:20:20.099 --> 00:20:22.219
Like there's actually, so I didn't talk about any of this, but

00:20:22.219 --> 00:20:27.300
there's like a whole marketplace of custom actions that people have developed

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:29.699
for use in GitHub Actions.

00:20:29.699 --> 00:20:33.939
And they can do things like deploy to Amazon S3 or

00:20:33.939 --> 00:20:37.500
Azure Cloud or wherever, basically.

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:42.300
And so you can basically, you can do a lot of some sophisticated

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:45.500
things with scheduled jobs like that, yeah.

00:20:46.699 --> 00:20:48.699
Fantastic, final hand for Jim.

00:20:48.699 --> 00:20:49.660
Jim, thank you very much.

00:20:49.819 --> 00:20:50.420
Yep.

00:20:50.420 --> 00:20:52.380
Thanks, accuracy.

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:53.219
See you.

00:20:53.219 --> 00:20:53.780
Bye bye.

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:55.780
Yep.

